article.description: Nnemkadi Ogwumike had 15 points and 10 rebounds as Stanford easily defeated UCLA 73-47 in a semifinal game at the Pac-10 tournament.
article.headline: Ogwumike double-double helps Cardinal cruise
article.linkText: No. 2 Stanford cruises into Pac-10 championship
article.story:
LOS ANGELES -- Nnemkadi Ogwumike acknowledges that playing basketball at the college level was a bit difficult to adjust to at the beginning of the season.

Now, she's getting it.

Ogwumike had 15 points and 10 rebounds and led No. 2 Stanford for the second straight night as the Cardinal easily defeated UCLA 73-47 in a semifinal game at the Pac-10 tournament Saturday night.

"As a freshman, you're just trying to get used to things," Ogwumike said. "Now I feel like I know what's going on. I've got the sets down."

And her coach and teammates are happy.

"It's always a challenge for every freshman coming in to learn our system, but I think she's done extremely well this year," center Jayne Appel said.

"When I look at the contributions that our freshmen are making -- Sarah Boothe played really well, Nnemka played really well, Lindy [La Rocque] played really well in both games -- that gives me more flexibility on the bench to be able to substitute," Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer said.

"That's getting more people involved and they keep each other accountable by doing that."

Besides Ogwumike, Boothe finished with 12 off the bench.

VanDerveer rested her starters for the most part, but paired them with reserves during the last stretch of the game.

Stanford (28-4) started the second half on a 20-3 run and led by 35 when Rosalyn Gold-Onwude scored on a layup with 11:55 remaining. Appel, who finished with 10 points and seven rebounds in 10 minutes, sparked the run with six consecutive points. Ogwumike also added six during that stretch.

Gold-Onwude, who had 12 points, finished it to give Stanford a 59-24 lead.

Jillian Harmon added 10 and Jeanette Pohlen had six assists for the Cardinal, the top seed in the tourney.

Stanford, winners of 15 straight, will face USC in the title game Sunday. The Trojans (17-14) upset No. 12 California 69-67 in a semifinal Saturday.

Besides a 12-2 run toward the end of the game, the fourth-seeded Bruins couldn't get things going on offense.

UCLA (19-12) shot 23 percent in the first half and didn't have a basket in the second until Antonye Nyingifa hit a jumper with 12:22 remaining.

"They did a great job of really disrupting us offensively," UCLA coach Nikki Caldwell said. "I thought we didn't make the extra passes; we were shooting contested shots and we didn't play as a unit and you have to. We have to be very disciplined in that action because Stanford is not going to break down too much in their defensive scheme."

They didn't.

The Cardinal put pressure on UCLA's guards throughout and rarely allowed the Bruins to drive the lanes. UCLA had 24 turnovers and had trouble getting its players open looks both inside and out. Stanford took advantage of mistakes by scoring 24 points.

"We had difficulty getting sets drawn," said Doreena Campbell, who finished with six points.

"I feel like we didn't have the same mentality we had against Oregon State," guard Darxia Morris said. "We knew Stanford was No. 2 and we should have brought it from the beginning."

Nina Earl led the Bruins with eight, while Morris added seven.

Campbell had a 3-pointer for UCLA during its late run and Allison Taka also added a trey to make it 61-36. But the Bruins couldn't muster a comeback from an 18-point halftime deficit.

UCLA, which lost three straight to Stanford this season, had trouble scoring in the first. Campbell had three points, all from the foul line in that half, while going 0-for-4 from the field.

Nyingifa, also a starter, had zero and was also 0-for-4 in the first.

The Cardinal got into trouble early with 12 fouls, and two starters had two apiece before halftime. But Stanford's bench stepped in to make key shots and help take a 39-21 halftime lead.

The Cardinal shot 59 percent during the first.

Gold-Onwude hit two 3s during a 10-2 run early on and Boothe, a freshman, had two easy baskets in the paint during a 13-4 scoring span to end the half.

UCLA tried shifting things on defense, but had no answer for Stanford's bigger post players. Ogwumike had eight in the first and the Cardinal outscored the Bruins 18-6 in the paint in the first.

Stanford is looking for its seventh conference tournament title and a young bench could prove to be the difference down the stretch.

"The class is developing very well and playing well at the right time," Appel said. "Our team depends on them a lot."

Ogwumike isn't reluctant to point out who her mentors are.

"We learn from the best," Ogwumike said, nodding to Appel.
